# {{.DisplayName}} CLI / API output fixtures

Golden files used by `providers/{{.Name}}` parser tests. Each `.txt` is
the raw stdout/stderr Webox observes after running the matching panel
command (or the verbatim JSON body returned by the panel API).

## Provenance policy

Every `<fixture>.txt` MUST have an accompanying `<fixture>.fixture.md`
file describing:

- `captured`: ISO date of the capture (or `inferred` when drafted from
  the panel docs ahead of a live capture).
- `account`: sanitised account identifier (NEVER the real login).
- `command`: the exact command invocation (or HTTP method + path).
- `sanitized`: list of replacements (login, domain, IP, token, etc.).
- `notes`: free-form gotchas (ANSI escapes? control bytes? trailing
  whitespace?).

Fixtures whose `captured: inferred` block out the parser's happy path
until a live capture replaces them.

## Sanitisation invariants

- Real user logins → `webox-test`.
- Real IP addresses → `203.0.113.10` (RFC 5737 documentation block).
- Real passwords → never committed. Replace with
  `REDACTED-NEVER-A-REAL-SECRET-<random>` so the redactor's regex flags
  any accidental leak.
- Real customer domains → `webox-test.example.com`.
- Real auth tokens → `REDACTED-NEVER-A-REAL-TOKEN-<random>`.

## Malicious fixtures

`*_malicious_*.txt` exists to exercise the parser's strict mode. It
embeds ANSI escape sequences, NUL bytes, command-injection-looking
substrings, and CR/LF mismatches. The parser MUST return
`providers.ErrUnknownOutputFormat` (or the relevant typed error) for
these — never a partially populated result and never the raw input
inside the error message.
